   "source": [
    "# Antenna Element"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "efec1d0e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy.io\n",
    "\n",
    "import neoradium as nr"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "0b128508",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create an antenna element with 65Â° beam width and maximum attenuation of 30db\n",
    "el = nr.AntennaElement(beamWidth=[65,65], maxAttenuation=30)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "1a973b7a",
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Depending on the input parameters the \"drawRadiation\" method can create different types of graphs. Here\n",
    "# we draw the directivity of our antenna element at the horizontal plane of zero elevation.\n",
    "radValues = el.drawRadiation(theta=90, viewAngles=(90,0), radiationType=\"Directivity\", normalize=True)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "2fa8de96",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Here the \"drawRadiation\" method is used to draw the Field values in the vertical plane at azimuth angle 0.\n",
    "radValues = el.drawRadiation(phi=0, radiationType=\"Field\", normalize=True)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "853b2495",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Here the \"drawRadiation\" method is used to draw a 3D graph of directivity.\n",
    "radValues = el.drawRadiation(radiationType=\"Directivity\", normalize=True, viewAngles=(90,0))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "00d6bbb3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Here the \"drawRadiation\" method is used again to draw a 3D graph of directivity. This time however, we are\n",
    "# specifying the angle resolution to be 2 degree. This makes the graph generation faster but also coarser than\n",
    "# the previous one. (The default angle resolution is 1 degree)\n",
    "radValues = el.drawRadiation(theta=np.arange(0,180.1,2), phi=np.arange(-180,180.1,2), \n",
    "                             radiationType=\"Directivity\", normalize=True, viewAngles=(90,0))"
   ]
  },
